==Timeline of world's highest observation decks== This is a timeline of the development of world's highest observation decks since the inauguration of the [[Washington Monument]] in 1885. {| class="sortable wikitable" style="text-align: center;" cellpadding="2" |- style="background: #ececec;" ! colspan="2" | Held record ! rowspan="2" | Name and Location ! rowspan="2" | Constructed ! rowspan="2" | Height of highest observation deck ! rowspan="2" | Notes |- style="background: #ececec;" ! From ! To |- |1885 |1889 |align="left" | [[Washington Monument]], [[Washington D.C.]], United States |1889 |{{Convert|152.3|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Was the world's tallest structure when completed. |- |1889 |1931 |align="left" | [[Eiffel Tower]], [[Paris]], France |1889 |{{Convert|275|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Two further observation decks 57 & 115 m. |- |1931 |1973 |align="left" | [[Empire State Building]], [[New York City]], United States |1931 |{{Convert|369|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="The Empire State Building"/> | A second observation deck is located on the 86th floor at 320 metres above ground. |- |1973 |1974 |align="left" | [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]], [[New York City]], United States ([[Top of the World Trade Center Observatories|''article'']]) |1973 |{{Convert|399.4|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Measured from [[sea level]], street level was 10 feet above sea level. Indoor observatory on the 107th floor of South Tower opened on April 4, 1973. Destroyed during the [[September 11 attacks]]. |- |1974 |1975 |align="left" | [[Sears Tower]] (since renamed Willis Tower), [[Chicago]], United States |1974 |{{Convert|412.4|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} | Measured from the Franklin Street entrance, 103rd floor observation deck opened on June 22, 1974 |- |1975 |1976 |align="left" | [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]], [[New York City]], United States ([[Top of the World Trade Center Observatories|''article'']]) |1973 |{{Convert|419.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Measured from [[sea level]], street level was 10 feet above sea level. Outdoor observatory on rooftop of the South Tower opened on December 15, 1975. Destroyed during the [[September 11 attacks]]. |- |1976 |2008 |align="left" | [[CN Tower]], [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada |1976 |{{Convert|446.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Two further observation decks 342 and 346 metres above ground. |- |2008 |2011 |align="left" | [[Shanghai World Financial Centre]], [[Shanghai]], [[People's Republic of China]] |2008 |{{Convert|474|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Other observation decks are at {{Convert|423|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|439|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}. |- |2011 |2014 |align="left" | [[Canton Tower]], [[Guangzhou]], [[People's Republic of China]] |2011 |{{Convert|488|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |The outdoor rooftop observation deck opened in December 2011. There are also several other indoor observation decks in the tower, the highest at {{convert|433.2|m|ft|abbr=on}}. |- |2014 |2016 |align="left" | [[Burj Khalifa]], [[Dubai]], [[UAE]] |2010 |555 m (1,821&nbsp;ft) |align="left" | Opened on October 15, 2014 on the 148th floor. There is another observation deck at {{convert|452.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} on the 124th floor, which has been open since the building was opened to the public. |- |2016 |present |align="left" | [[Shanghai Tower]], [[Shanghai]], [[China]] |2015 |562.1 m (1,844&nbsp;ft) |align="left" | Opened on July 1, 2016. there are also 2 more observation decks on the 118th and 119th floor, at 546 and 552 meters respectively.
|}
